<title>New Strategy Required for Cleaner Air -- PFF</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> 
<blockquote><ul>
<a href="/pff/"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
For Immediate Release<br>
July 10, 1996<br>
Contact:  Rick ODonnell<br>
202/289-8928<p>

<h2>New Strategy Required for Cleaner Air</h2>
The Progress & Freedom Foundation today released a white paper urging for the creation of local Environmental Innovation Areas (EIAs) that recognize the variation in environmental conditions across America and thus will serve to solve regional pollution problems.  The paper calls for using EIAs as a means of promoting alternative fuel vehicles to meet clean air requirements and petroleum import reduction goals.

"Different regions face different pollution problems, and thus they must be given the flexibility to meet clean air requirements in ways best suited for their region," said Bruce Yandle, a co-author of the white paper, titled <i><a href="/pff/clean/exec.html">Clean Air and Emerging Alternative Fuel Vehicles:  A Time for Environmental Innovation Areas</a></i>.  "Alternative fuel -- or non petroleum-based -- vehicles pollute less and should serve as an important component of many regions strategies for meeting clean air goals."<p>

The white paper calls for an end to Federal fuel taxes that discriminate against alternative fuels.  In their place it urges incentives for states and regions to design fuel taxes that encourage the appropriate use of cleaner burning fuels in their area.  The authors also argue that alternative fuel vehicles are a lower-cost way to improve automobile efficiency than Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards.<p>

"By removing barriers to expanded alternative fuel vehicle use and development of other improved technologies, these proposals would reduce the cost of achieving environmental and national energy security goals," argues the paper.<p>

Copies of the white paper are available from the Foundation by calling 202/289-8928 or on its Internet homepage:  www.pff.org.  The Progress & Freedom Foundation is a private, non-profit, non-partisan idea center established in 1993 to create a positive vision of the future founded in the historic principles of the American Idea.  It brings together a diverse group of thinkers and policy experts and shares their work with the American people through seminars, conferences, publications and broadcasts.<p>

<p>
