<HEAD>
<title>1995 National Orientation Conference</title>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<center><h2>New Legislators Get Lessons in Free-Market Principles, Limited-Government Philosophy</h2>
<P>
<B>CONTACT: Kerry Jackson or Noel Card (202) 466-3800</B></center>
<hr>
<center>[ <a href="#cred">Credentialing Procedure</a> | <a href="#issues">1995 NOC Issue Sessions</a> ]</center>
<hr>
<P>
<B>WASHINGTON, D.C.</B>, December 1, 1995-- More than 400 state
legislators from across the country, many of them newly elected,
will attend an orientation conference in Washington, D.C., December
5-9 at the Washington Renaissance Hotel that will be key in the
continuing liberation of America from six decades of intrusive
public policy.
<P>
&quot;This is the perfect opportunity for us to impart to these
new legislators the importance of limited-government, free-market
principles that are our nation's Founders' legacy and the standards
of a just and prosperous nation,&quot; said Colorado State Senator
Ray Powers, the National Chairman of the American Legislative
Exchange Council (ALEC), which sponsors the National Orientation
Conference (NOC) every year. &quot;By educating the new legislators
in the Jeffersonian principles, we are pushing the conservative
movement beyond last year's revolution. What we accomplish at
this conference will shape public policy in the states and nationally
for years to come.&quot;
<P>
<B>Confirmed speakers</B> at this year's NOC include: US. SENATOR
SPENCER ABRAHAM (R Mich.); US. SENATOR JOSEPH LIEBERMAN (D-Conn.);
retired SENATOR MALCOLM WALLOP, former ATTORNEY GENERAL EDWIN
MEESE, MINNESOTA GOVERNOR ARNE CARLSON; CONGRESSMEN ERNEST ISTOOK
(R-Okla.) and JOEL HEFLEY (R Colo..); ED CRANE, President and
CEO of the Cato Institute; JOSEPH BAST, President of the Heartland
Institute; PAUL WEYRICH, President Of the Free Congress Foundation.
<P>
Speakers who are invited but have not yet accepted include U.S.
SUPREME COURT JUSTICE CLARENCE THOMAS, U.S. SENATORS BOB DOLE
(R Kan.), JOHN McCAIN (R Ariz.) and TRENT LOTT (R Miss.), CONGRESSMEN
JOHN KASICH (R-Ohio), THOMAS BLILEY (R-Va),   PENNSYLVANIA GOVERNOR
TOM RIDGE, MICHIGAN GOVERNOR JOHN ENGLER, NEW JERSEY GOVERNOR
CHRISTINE TODD WHITMAN, MASSACHUSETTS GOVERNOR WILLIAM WELD, VIRGINIA
GOVERNOR GEORGE ALLEN, NEBRASKA GOVERNOR BEN NELSON and UTAH GOVERNOR
MIKE LEAVITT.
<P>
Also scheduled for the NOC is the presentation of the <B>1995
Warren Brookes Award for Excellence in Journalism</B> to Don Lanbro,
chief political correspondent for the Washington Times. Lambro
will be honored at a luncheon Friday, December 8 beginning at
12:15 p.m.
<P>
Last year's NOC was the largest one in ALEC's history. Attended
by 412 legislators, it was more than twice the size of any previous
NOC. About 250 private sector members attended, as well. Similar
attendance is expected at this year's meeting.
<P><a name="cred"></a>
<B>Credentialing Procedure</B>:
<P>
Anyone considering covering any parts of the meeting should pre-register
by calling Kerry Jackson or Noel Card at (202) 466-3800. Pre-registration
can also be done by faxing a brief request. Reporters who have
pre-registered will be able to pick up their credentials in the
media office by presenting their official press or company ID
at any time during business hours. Those registering on-site must
present an official press or company ID or a request from an editor
written on a company letterhead.
<P>
<hr width="50%">
<P><a name="issues"></a>
<center><h3>Issue Sessions at the 1995 NOC</h3>
<P>
<i>The Future of Conservatism in the States
<br>Free Market Health Care policy
<br>Free Market Environmental policy
<br>Telecommunications Reform
<br>Balanced Budget Amendment Tax Reform
<br>Tort Reform
<br>Federalism
<br>Campaigns and Elections '95
</i>
<P>
<hr width="75%">
<P>
<I>ALEC is a 5O1 (c)(3) nonprofit educational and public policy
organization as defined by the Internal Revenue Service. ALEC
is  governed by a 21-member Board of Directors of state legislators,
which is advised by a 23-member Private Enterprise Board, comprised
of representatives of major foundations and corporate sponsors.
ALEC was founded in 1973 by a small group of Democratic and Republican
state legislators who shred a common commitment to the principles
of free markets, limited government and individual liberty. It
is the largest bipartisan, individual membership organization
of state legislators in the country with nearly 3,000 members.</I>

