<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>John Baden Biography</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> 

<center><h2>John A. Baden</h2> </center>
<HR><blockquote>
John A. Baden is founder and chairman of the Foundation for Research on Economics and the Environment (FREE).  FREE is a 501 (c)(3) market-oriented research and education foundation.  The main FREE office is in Bozeman, Montana and a second is in Seattle, Washington.  Dr. Baden is a leader in developing the New Resource Economics, an incentive-based approach to environmental and natural resource management that stresses private property rights and the market process as policy instruments.<P>
Dr. Baden received his Ph.D. from Indiana University in 1969 and then was awarded a National Science Foundation Postdoctoral Fellowship in environmental policy.  He has held endowed professorships, received teaching awards and is the author or editor of seven books, numerous articles on energy and natural resources, and a syndicated column originating in <i>The Seattle Times.</i><P>
John Baden is a member of the Mont Pelerin Society, has served two terms on the National Petroleum Council, and has served as President of the Association of Private Enterprise Education.  He recently resigned his Affiliate Professorship at the University of Washington School of Business to devote his full attention to FREE.  For the past four years he has organized a series of four week-long seminars in environmental economics and policy for federal judges.<P>
Dr. Baden and his wife, Professor Ramona Marotz-Baden, both avid bicyclists, own and operate a ranch in the Gallatin Valley of Montana and an orchard in the Yakima Valley of Washington. 
</blockquote>
<P> <br><center>
