<html>
<head>
<title>Capital Letters</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="/abic/images/capcry.gif" ALT="Capital Crying" align="left">
<p>
<center>
<hr>
<img src="/abic/images/letters.gif" ALT="CAPITAL LETTERS">
<br>
<B>America's Political Advice Column</b>
</center>
<hr>
<p>
<center>
* * *
</center>
<P><br><br><br>

<pre>
Dear Cleta:
<p>
I live in Glenside, PA, but my family pays more taxes to the city of 
Philadelphia than we do to our home township and county combined.  
Now Mayor Rendell has come out to my town and said we aren't paying 
enough!  We moved out of Philadelphia because we couldn't afford private 
school for our kids at the same time we were supporting patronage and 
perks for Rendell's friends.  How can I help him get it?  
<p>
--Robbed by the City of Brother Love
</pre>
<p>
Dear Robbed:
<p>
I presume you are talking about the income tax paid by people who work in Philadelphia but who live outside of the city.  Is that what you're talking about?  If not, write back and clarify.  If it is, you are taxed without representation.  You pay taxes on income to a jurisdiction in which you have no voting representation.  I'm wondering if the constitutionality of such a system has ever been tested in the courts.  Maybe you should contact one of the public interest legal foundations and discuss filing a lawsuit challenging the constitutionality of such a system.  
<p>
Here are some suggestions:  
<p>
Institute for Justice<br>
Washington, DC<br>
202-457-4240<br>
<p>
National Legal Center for the Public Interest<br>
Washington, DC<br>
202-296-1683<br>
<p>
Washington Legal Foundation<br>
Washington, DC<br>
202-588-0302<br>
<p>
***
<p>
<pre>
Dear Cleta:
<p>
Here is a possible idea for a "10" Veep nominee.  How about former 
governor Casey of Penn.? Yes, he is a Democrat but that makes the 
choice more provacative and interesting.  He comes from an area that 
is key to winning the election.  If he can pass any health concerns, 
he would be a great choice.
<p>
What do you think?
<p>
--Frank 
<p>
</pre>
Dear Frank:  
<p>
I think the Republican convention would go nuts if Bob Dole nominates a Democrat for Vice President.  Did you hear the furor when Dole floated Sam Nunn's name a few months ago?  I admire Bob Casey and his courage, but his health isn't great -- and with Bob Dole's age it makes the Vice Presidential candidate's health a key issue for the fall.  Nice try -- but it's probably a non-starter.  
<p>
***
<p>
<pre>
Dear Cleta:
<p>
I have long opposed the minimum wage as an infrngement into American 
private business by a fat over-regulating government.  I resent Uncle 
telling me how much I must pay someone to perform a given task.  How 
can we stop this and other unwarranted entanglement by government in 
private citizens' interests?
<p>
--Doc
</pre><p>
Dear Doc:  
<p>
The way you stop the federal government is by electing members of Congress who are willing to say "no" to their own constituents -- and get the government out of our hair.  That means you should make yourself known to candidates and incumbents and don't vote for anyone who is for higher taxes, more spending and bigger government.  That means you should vote for people who are for LIMITED government, which means term limits, balanced budget amendment, lower taxes.  If we are to create an environment where every person can realize the American Dream, we're going to have to organize the people who think like we do -- and fight back against the powerful interests who want a government that grows and grows.  If you want to help with that effort, write back and add your name to our list of the "Dream Team":  people who will work for real politcal change in America. We'll tell you how.
<p>

<p><br>

<center>
<a href="http://www.townhall.com">Town Hall</a> - <a href="http://www.abic.org">Americans
Back In Charge</a> - <a href="/abic/cl-emailer.html">e-mail Cleta Mitchell</a>
<p>
</center>
</body>
