<html>
<head>
<title>E-Mail Congresssman Gephardt -- SBSC</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">

<p>

You can use this form to send a letter to Minority Leader Gephardt concerning the Davis-Bacon Act. A letter has already been prepared for you, but please customize it to fit your needs. Remember to sign the letter!<p>

Here is Congressman Gephardt's email address if you want to send additional comments:
<a href="mailto:demldr@hr.house.gov">demldr@hr.house.gov</a>

<p>
<form action="/townhall/scripts/sbsc-email.cgi" method="post">
Your email address:<br>
<input type="text" size="60" name="a-email">
<p>
The subject of your email:<br>
<input type="text" size="60" name="b-subj" value="Davis-Bacon Act">
<p>
Your message:<br>
<textarea cols="60" rows="10" wrap="physical" name="c-text">
Dear Congressman:


As a small business owner and taxpayer, I strongly encourage
you to support efforts to repeal the Davis-Bacon Act.  This
outdated, discriminatory act has cost hard working taxpayers
billions, and inhibited the opportunities of small
construction firms and unskilled (mostly minority) workers.

Davis-Bacon is an example of what's wrong with Washington.
This anti-market law has no place in our government, yet
lawmakers elected for change have been unable to repeal it.
I am shocked to hear that some Members of Congress actually
want to "reform" Davis-Bacon by expanding it.

When the Republicans pulled Davis-Bacon out of the budget
reconciliation bill they sent a signal to voters.  Such
activity told the public the majority party wasn't willing
to aggressively support bold regulatory and fiscal reform.
The confidence I had in Congress since the '94 election is
being eroded by the failures of this Congress to enact bold
reforms.  This failure only benefits special interests at
the expense of all taxpayers and our system of free
enterprise.

As a member of the Small Business Survival Committee, I
understand the implications of keeping a law like Davis-
Bacon on the books.  Time should have run out for Davis-
Bacon, and Members of Congress should repeal this harmful
law.

Sincerely,
</textarea>
<p>
<input type="submit" value="Submit mail">
<input type="reset" value="Clear the form">
<input type="hidden" name="d-to" value="demldr@hr.house.gov">
<input type="hidden" name="outfile" value="/usr/users/www-user/output/sbsc/letter-congress.output">
</form>

</body>
